- OS_SelectSingle_Impl: Although called like a normal function, if this symbol is a macro or inline function (or otherwise expands in caller scope) it could modify the StateFlags identifier in the caller. Even if a true function, its prototype/implementation confirms it does not write to the caller's parameter variable (only to the pointed-to object).
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: This is called prior to any use of StateFlags and could be a macro or inline helper that expands into code that (unusually) modifies caller-scope variables. Inspecting its implementation rules out any hidden modification of the function parameters.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Similar rationale as OS_ObjectIdGetById — if implemented as a macro/inline it might expand into code in caller scope. Verify it does not modify StateFlags.
- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: The static call graph shows these unit-test stub/instrumentation symbols as callees of OS_SelectSingle. Some test harnesses implement instrumentation as macros or inline hooks that expand into the caller and could potentially reference or modify the StateFlags identifier. Include their definitions to confirm they do not alter the pointer parameter.

Note: The MISRA rule of interest forbids modifying the function parameter variable (the pointer itself). The only plausible ways the parameter variable can be changed in this body are via macros or inlined code that expand in the caller scope, so the next-stage analysis must examine the concrete definitions/implementations of the listed symbols to conclusively determine compliance.
